{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PoEyLU2qyX2yRuSah23a2J","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still the same error: `unable to find real backend for alternative backend demo-canary-echo-80. Deleting.`\n\nThis is persistent. Let me understand this better. The nginx ingress controller is saying it can't find the canary backend. But I verified that the canary-echo endpoint is `10.244.0.92:5678`. \n\nWait, maybe the issue is that the canary endpoint port mapping is wrong. The controller is looking for port 80, but the actual pod is on port 5678. However, I defined the Service to map port 80 → targetPort 5678. So the endpoint should be registered with port 5678.\nThe \"-80\" in the error message indicates the controller is looking at service port 80. Let me check if the canary-echo service actually has ready endpoints at the time the ingress controller processes it—the error typically occurs when there are no ready endpoints available, even though I can see the endpoint listed.\n\nLooking at the logs more carefully, there's a successful backend reload at 08:59:56, but that happened before the endpoints were ready. After that, only errors appear—no more successful reloads. The controller isn't re-reading the endpoints after they become available because reloads are triggered by configuration changes, not endpoint availability. Even though the endpoints are now up, the controller never reconciled the configuration after they came online, so it's still trying to use the old state where the backend didn't exist. endpoints either. Let me reconsider the controller's behavior here—the \"unable to find real backend\" error specifically means the canary ingress can't locate its corresponding primary ingress for the same hostname. I'm checking whether `canary-stable` was actually applied before `canary-canary`, since the order matters for the controller to recognize the relationship between them.\n\nLooking at the timestamps, `canary-stable` was validated and synced before `canary-canary` was processed, so the primary ingress should have been in place. The error about the decoy `canary-alt` ingress is separate, but the real issue is that `canary-canary` is trying to register as a canary backend but can't find its corresponding primary backend to attach to.\n\nI'm wondering if the problem is related to path matching — `canary-stable` has both `/health` (Prefix) and `/` (Exact), while `canary-canary` only has `/` (Exact). The nginx controller might require the canary ingress paths to match the primary ingress paths exactly, or maybe the primary backend hasn't fully initialized by the time the canary controller tries to reference it.\n\nLet me test whether the stable backend works on its own first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1439,"cache_read_input_tokens":46541,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1439},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae239c15-9c85-4b8c-9fbc-d508a064eda6","uuid":"5301254c-91d8-43a8-89ae-7914e7dbb3c2","request_id":"req_011Cc6fdR7V6U3ZDtVMQgrRL"}
