{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KRQTWSz7WCwxtxg7Nng3yS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Key findings:\n1. `set $service_name \"stable-echo\"` - Nginx knows the service name\n2. `set $proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\"` - But the upstream is set to default!\n\nWait, I need to re-read more of this. The nginx-ingress sets:\n1. `$service_name \"stable-echo\"` - the service name\n2. `$proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\"` - the upstream to use (NOTE: this is the DEFAULT)\n\nThen `rewrite_by_lua_file` runs BEFORE the `set $proxy_upstream_name` line... wait, no. \n\nI'm getting confused about nginx's execution phases. The `rewrite_by_lua_file` directive runs during the rewrite phase, which happens before the proxy phase where `proxy_pass` executes. But `set` directives are processed at configuration load time to initialize variables, not at request time. So the order of execution is actually: rewrite phase (where the Lua script runs) happens before the proxy phase, and by that point the variables have already been initialized from the config. Setting nginx variables in order... So the actual execution order in nginx is: all `set` directives run first in sequence, then the Lua hook fires during the rewrite phase, meaning the Lua code can read and modify whatever those `set` directives established. After that come the header and log phase hooks.\n\nThe access log shows `[upstream-default-backend]` even though the Lua code should theoretically be updating `$proxy_upstream_name` to route to the demo backend. Since the log is captured during the log phase after the request completes, it would reflect whatever value the Lua code set—so if the upstream is still showing as the default backend, the Lua code must not actually be updating that variable. I'm trying to figure out why the Lua code isn't making that change.\n\nThe Lua rewrite code constructs the upstream name from the service variables and checks if it exists in a backends dictionary, setting `$proxy_upstream_name` accordingly. But here's the issue: the backends dictionary that the Lua code reads from might be a separate shared memory store that's different from the `/configuration/backends` HTTP API endpoint. The API endpoint shows what's currently being served and gets updated dynamically, but the Lua code might be reading from a stale or differently-populated shared memory dict.\n\nActually, wait—both should be using the same Lua shared dictionary, so if `/configuration/backends` shows `demo-stable-echo-80`, the Lua rewrite code should find it too. The timing matters here: the backends dict gets updated, and then each request reads from it at request time. So if the dict contains `demo-stable-echo-80`, the routing should work. But the access log shows `[upstream-default-backend]` instead, which suggests the Lua code isn't finding the upstream. I need to look more carefully at how nginx-ingress distinguishes between static nginx upstream blocks and the dynamic Lua backends dictionary—the `$proxy_upstream_name` variable might not be getting set properly in the first place. The issue is that when nginx-ingress generates the config, it sets `$proxy_upstream_name` to the actual backend only if that service has endpoints available at config-generation time—otherwise it defaults to `upstream-default-backend`. Since the config shows `upstream-default-backend` for stable-echo, it means the controller had no endpoints cached for that service during the last reload at 09:02:39. But that's puzzling because stable-echo was deployed around 08:58 with its pod Running by 09:00, so it should have had endpoints for over two minutes by the time of the reload. This suggests either a caching bug in the controller or the endpoints are in an unexpected state.\n\nLooking at the controller logs, I see warnings from 08:58 and 08:59 saying stable-echo has no active endpoints, but by 09:02:39 those should have resolved. The discrepancy might be that the endpoint didn't become \"active\" in the nginx-ingress sense—perhaps the readiness probe hadn't passed yet when the config was generated.\n\nActually, wait—the `kubectl get endpoints` output shows `10.244.0.91:5678`, which means the endpoint is already there. If the pod wasn't ready, it wouldn't appear in the endpoint list at all. So maybe the issue is that the nginx-ingress controller's internal cache is out of sync with what kubectl sees—the informer cache might still think there are no endpoints for stable-echo even though they've been added.\n\nLet me reconsider the timing here. When canary-stable was applied and nginx reloaded at 09:02:39, what was the actual state of the stable-echo endpoints at that moment? Rather than keep digging into this, I should try a different approach—the canary routing in nginx-ingress is handled by Lua code, and the issue might be simpler than I'm making it.\n\nIf nginx's config has `$proxy_upstream_name` pointing to the default backend because stable-echo had no endpoints when the config was last reloaded, then all requests to canary.example.com would hit the 404 backend. The solution is to force nginx to reload its config now that endpoints are actually available, either by modifying the ingress annotation or by deleting and recreating both the stable-echo and canary ingresses once I've confirmed all endpoints are ready.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2895,"cache_read_input_tokens":60911,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2895},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae239c15-9c85-4b8c-9fbc-d508a064eda6","uuid":"02211022-730e-4164-89b3-c8c15e8c5224","request_id":"req_011Cc6fyqbCajEwXwAdTDwML"}
