{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ThqSFSrehUs91u64H6ond3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture!\n\nThe `get_balancer()` function:\n1. Reads `ngx.var.proxy_upstream_name` (which is the nginx `$proxy_upstream_name` variable)\n2. Looks up `balancers[backend_name]` for that name\n3. If found, checks if it should route to alternative (canary) backend\n4. If the balancer has `alternative_backends`, and the routing condition matches, it switches to the alternative balancer\n\nKey insight:\n- The STATIC nginx.conf has `set $proxy_upstream_name \"upstream-default-backend\"` for the `canary.example.com location /`\n- When the Lua code reads this variable, it finds `upstream-default-backend` in the balancers dictionary (pointing to 127.0.0.1:8181), so it routes there and gets a 404\n- The reason the nginx.conf was generated with `upstream-default-backend` is that stable-echo had no endpoints in the nginx-ingress controller cache at the time the config was created, which the logs confirm with timestamps around 08:58:15 through 08:59:18\n- Even when the canary-stable ingress was processed at 09:02:39, stable-echo still had no endpoints, but they appeared afterward and the Lua balancers dict was updated dynamically with the correct endpoint, yet the nginx.conf still references the default upstream instead of the actual service upstream.\n\nThe real issue is that nginx.conf needs to be regenerated with the correct `$proxy_upstream_name` variable pointing to the actual service. I can force this by touching an annotation on the stable ingress to trigger a reload, but first I should verify the endpoints are actually in the controller's store. Looking at the backends API, `demo-stable-echo-80` is already there with the right endpoint, so the Lua side has the data it needs.\n\nThe problem is the timing: nginx.conf was generated before the endpoints existed, so it still references `upstream-default-backend`. When requests come in, the Lua balancer reads that stale variable from nginx.conf and routes to the wrong upstream. I need to trigger a reload now that the endpoints are established. There might be a timing issue where the endpoint appears in the Kubernetes API but hasn't propagated to the nginx-ingress controller's cache yet. Let me force another reload immediately and check what actually gets configured.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":439,"cache_read_input_tokens":70365,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":439},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae239c15-9c85-4b8c-9fbc-d508a064eda6","uuid":"e3124203-a497-479f-8574-3a59b5f0eff5","request_id":"req_011Cc6g6ojmmLhKgYCLm98mM"}
