lied at runtime.\n\nThe real problem is that the Lua balancer uses the `$proxy_upstream_name` variable from the nginx config to determine which backend to route to. Even if `demo-stable-echo-80` exists in the Lua backends dictionary, if the config says `upstream-default-backend`, that's what the balancer will look up and use. So I need to trigger a config reload after the stable-echo endpoints become active in the controller's state.\n\nBut I'm stuck because the controller's template keeps generating `upstream-default-backend` regardless of when I reload. Let me check if the endpoint is actually ready—the pod shows 1/1 containers running and the endpoint is in the ready addresses list, not notReadyAddresses. So the endpoint should be active. Maybe I need to try a different ingress configuration, like switching from `pathType: Exact` to `pathType: Prefix` for the root path.\n\nActually, looking at the nginx.conf output more carefully, I see the issue: the location block is setting `$proxy_upstream_name` to `upstream-default-backend` instead of the actual service upstream name like `demo-stable-echo-80`. This fallback to the default backend only happens if the service has no endpoints at the time the controller generates the config, or there's some other condition triggering it. I need to dig into the nginx-ingress controller's logic to understand when it uses the default backend versus the actual upstream name.\n\nThe real problem might be a timing mismatch between when endpoints become available and when the nginx config gets reloaded. If the service had no endpoints when the config was generated, it would use the default backend. Even if endpoints appear later and get added to the Lua dict, the nginx.conf still references the default backend. The only way to fix this would be to trigger another config reload after the endpoints become active. Given that the endpoint appeared at 08:59:01 but the canary-stable was applied at 09:08, there's a nine-minute gap where something should have triggered a reload but apparently didn't. I'm realizing the Go controller's informer cache and the dynamic Lua backends dict are separate systems, so the controller might have a stale view of the endpoints even though the Lua dict is up to date. Let me check if the http-echo pod has a readiness probe and whether it's actually marked as ready from the ingress controller's perspective.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1592,"cache_read_input_tokens":73176,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1592},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae239c15-9c85-4b8c-9fbc-d508a064eda6","uuid":"92bce156-cdbc-436e-9836-e526d87d917d","request_id":"req_011Cc6gDHEArtkrBbLWgxra4"}
